Very very early days, but I would expect these to be the frontrunners in the upcoming Labour leadership race. https://t.co/pron6yW69D

@Benpowelluk That's the point my sleep-deprived brain has been trying to make. Arguably Labour had an even worse time of things in 2015 as the EU ref wasn't a dominant factor, and would've only needed ~10m votes to get power. This time 10.2m votes gets you barely 200 seats.

For now though, the party needs a new leader and deputy. Despite the losses last night, there are a fine few potential successors elected who could take the party forward. They could start by, say, picking someone from the north...

Free dental health checks for all? Excellent, simple, popular idea, and doesn't sound too expensive to implement. Removing charity status from private schools? Er, wouldn't be my first thought on fixing the country...

And finally; I loved the Labour manifesto. 1997 was the last time, pre-Corbyn era, anyone should get legitimately excited about a Labour manifesto. And yet... I concede there's too much in it. I can't remember half of what was promised, and it meant the best policies were diluted

Wales never really seemed to feature too much on Labour's central office campaign either. 2017 excepted, Labour's fortunes have felt like managed decline since the latter days of the Blair era, like Scotland.

A massive hint should have been when lots of regional newspapers produced front pages calling for a 'Manifesto for the North'. One of those, done right, could've really reconnected with Labour's heartlands. It's something they can still do on future.
As for Labour, where to go from here? Brexit may be less of a polarising issue at the next election, but there are still other factors they should have prepared for in #GE2019 .

The next chapter is whether all those 14.5 million people will be happy with the exact type of Brexit that will be approved by Parliament in the upcoming weeks. And even then, if they'd 'reward' the Tories that took them out of the EU with future voting loyalty.
Basically, what I'm saying is, don't be surprised that 14.5 million people in this country have just voted for parties which want to push through with Brexit.

As 'bad' as the Tories did in 2017, they picked up 13.6 million votes, plus there were the 600k Ukip votes. The technicalities of Brexit had yet to be defined but the high turnout, mirroring the high turnout in the EU referendum, showed there was a big demand for it.

The sign was there in 2015, when Conservatives and Ukip took over 15 million votes between them. Labour had a bad time in that year's election but frankly would've done a lot worse had Ukip not split the Tory vote.

The overriding factor in the last five years is that 12-14 million voters in the UK really, really want a Brexit of some sort, and little has been said or done to change their minds during that time. #GE2019

Finally, all four victorious Independent councillors did superbly, each earning the maximum number of votes in their respective wards. Former Tory Eveleigh Moore Dutton took nearly two-thirds of the Tarporley vote, while Martin Barker strengthened his grip on Parkgate.

The shock result was seeing the Green Party storm to a convincing victory in Helsby. The party's candidates had a number of very respectable vote shares elsewhere in Cheshire West, in many cases significantly up on their 2015 showings.

The Liberal Democrats will be pleased at getting a presence back on CWaC with two seats, having been wiped out in 2015, but they didn't quite make the headway seen elsewhere in England. Nevertheless, gaining Farndon was a good result.
The Conservatives, meanwhile, will feel reasonably ok after holding on to more than three-quarters of their seats, given the pasting the party has taken elsewhere in England.

I don't think Labour will be too unhappy, despite losing majority control of the council. There was a bit of gnashing of teeth after they lost two crucial seats by under a dozen votes, but to be clearly the largest party after a significant boundary reshuffle will please them.
